</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>ACR105:v97#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="ACR105"/><meta name="dc:title" content="ACR &#xA;              105-&#xA;                CHAPTERED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div width="100%" style="text-align:center;"><div id="bill_num_title_chap"><span style="text-align:center;font-weight:bold;font-size:1.1em;font-family:'Times New Roman'; "><b>
                Assembly Concurrent Resolution
              
                        No. 105</b></span></div><div style="text-align:center;padding-top: 1.0em;padding-bottom: 1.2em;" id="chap_num_title_chap"><span style="font-size:1.4em;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-weight:normal;">
                      CHAPTER 192</span></div></div><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> Relative to the music industry in California. </span></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center">
                  
                  [<span style="  font-size: 1.3em">
                Filed with
              </span><span style="  font-size: 1.3em">
                Secretary of State
              </span> <span style="font-size: 13pt">September 23, 2025.
                      </span>]
                </div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">ACR 105, McKinnor.
                          Music industry.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This measure would recognize the contributions of the music industry to the economic and cultural well-being of the state, its population, and its overall reputation as a worldwide leader in artistic and creative freedom.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><span class="Resolution" title="source: /caml:MeasureDoc/caml:Resolution&#xA;    "><span class="Whereas" id="id_DC643685-36EE-4EA5-9E1E-38BD6BF2C4F2"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Music plays an outsized role in American culture and is unique among art forms in being so widely enjoyed and shared, creating connections between people across geography and even time; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_3843E982-0FC2-46DC-A01A-8FE86134EB15"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Music has a significant, broad, and growing impact on the California economy; and </div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_0A0819A3-DECD-46B6-9455-89601BB96A69"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, California has been a long-time anchor for the arts and entertainment industries and has fostered a vibrant music community that continues to reflect the diversity of America’s landscape and enrich the lives of fans all around the world; and </div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_4B78F50E-1167-4411-A22A-0D90DD049A28"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Its unparalleled music history has breathed life into entire music movements, including early surf rock icons, the Monterey International Pop festival, the psychedelic rock revolution of the 1960s, the country-folk-rock “Laurel Canyon” sound of the 1970s, the new wave and punk movements of the 1980s, and West Coast hip-hop. California is also one of the world’s foremost centers of regional Mexican music, including norteño and banda, and is home to historic musicians like The Kingston Trio, The Beach Boys, Ritchie Valens, Cher, the Grateful Dead, Santana, Fleetwood Mac, the Eagles, Tupac Shakur, Green Day, X, Los Lobos, Red Hot Chili Peppers, Dr. Dre, Billie Eilish, Los Tigres del Norte, and Kendrick Lamar, to name a few; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_2A3C19D9-89D5-474C-B4F6-6F4662149BC4"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, California is home to some of the most iconic live music venues in the country, among them The Fillmore in San Francisco and the Troubadour in Hollywood; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_EDEE06A8-1B25-4734-AF70-1815E4DD2E09"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, The music industry occupies an important place as a driver of California’s economic prosperity and growth; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_448FF6C6-9EFD-4217-A24A-E419F57436A5"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, A recent industrywide “50 States of Music” report showed California is the top state in the nation for measures of music industry earnings, employment, and value-added businesses that support artists and companies; and </div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_EC5D4B78-7BEC-449F-8881-4099F22F64A9"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Music contributes $51,000,000,000 to California’s economy and supports over 460,000 jobs and over 80,000 music establishments in our state; and </div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_CA005C35-0852-4F0E-A0EF-5876FCD197A2"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Music supports local businesses all across the state, including “a remarkable surge in business activity” from annual festivals, including $600 million from the world-renowned Coachella and Stagecoach festivals alone, which, according to Palm Springs local news, provides a “vital” boost “for many small businesses” in the area; and </div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_0A0FF9BB-3FFF-46D4-8833-4BE60F0B3416"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Nationally, employment supported by the U.S. music industry also increased substantially during the period 2017 to 2020, exceeding a 17 percent increase in jobs; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_6651726E-EDAA-4B1B-BB47-83A65E877ADB"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, The music community industry has been able to remain vibrant, relevant, and reinvent itself to embrace new technologies and meet consumer desires and needs in an increasingly digitalized world; now, therefore, be it</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_441FE2D1-B08E-49E0-AD38-02AEE8DE4B98"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved by the Assembly of the State of California, the Senate thereof concurring, That the Legislature recognizes the contributions of the music industry to the economic and cultural well-being of the state, its population, and its overall reputation as a worldwide leader in artistic and creative freedom; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_24967AC0-F02B-49B1-8651-25A7135E0461"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That the Chief Clerk of the Assembly transmit copies of this resolution to the author for appropriate distribution.</div></span></span></div></body></html>
